results.reasoning: Midline pineal region homogeneous, intensely enhancing mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus in an adult male; biopsy then excellent response to radiotherapy is classic for pineal germinoma — highly radiosensitive. Imaging and clinical course favor intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma).

Pelvic CT-urography shows irregular, very high-attenuation material in the pelvis that matches the distribution of contrast seen on the preoperative barium enema; 3D images confirm dense particulate deposits consistent with extraluminal enteric (barium) material rather than a fluid abscess or urinoma (no progressive urinary contrast leak or hydronephrosis). Therefore most likely diagnosis is extraluminal enteric material.

Lobulated volar tendon-sheath mass with low T2 signal and heterogeneous enhancement consistent with hemosiderin-rich, solid lesion rather than a fluid ganglion; favors giant-cell tumor of tendon sheath (localized PVNS).

CT and US show a left upper‑quadrant, thin‑walled multilocular cystic mass with surrounding inflammatory changes; patient has fever and leukocytosis. Imaging and clinical picture most consistent with an infected mesenteric/omental lymphangioma (lymphangioma with inflammatory changes). Non‑pancreatic pseudocyst lacks pancreatitis history, enteric duplication/enteric cyst would be closely associated with bowel wall, and mesothelial cyst is less likely in this location.

Teenage patient with a large multilocular adnexal mass and elevated androstenedione consistent with an androgen-secreting tumor; MRI shows cystic mass with solid nodules and histology demonstrates retiform and poorly differentiated features characteristic of a Sertoli–Leydig cell tumour (SCLT).

Midline pineal-region homogenously enhancing mass causing obstructive hydrocephalus with biopsy confirmation and excellent radiotherapy response — classic for intracranial germ cell tumour (germinoma). Imaging shows central/engulfed pineal calcification and homogeneous enhancement, favoring germinoma over pineoblastoma, tectal glioma, meningioma or dermoid.

Preoperative barium enema and postoperative CT show high-attenuation material in the pelvis consistent with extraluminal enteric contrast/barium leakage (extraluminal enteric material), not a simple seroma/urinoma or ascites.

Volar wrist mass arising from tendon sheath, solid heterogeneous lesion with internal low-signal areas on T2/gradient and avid enhancement consistent with hemosiderin and solid tumor—typical for giant cell tumor of tendon sheath (tenosynovial giant cell tumor).

CT and US show a unilocular mesenteric cyst with internal debris, thick enhancing wall and surrounding fat stranding consistent with an inflamed mesenteric (non-pancreatic) pseudocyst; clinical fever and leukocytosis support an infected pseudocyst.

13-year-old with virilizing biochemical profile (↑ Δ4-androstenedione), large solid-cystic adnexal mass on MRI and histology showing retiform/poorly differentiated sex-cord pattern — classic for Sertoli–Leydig cell tumour.
